 | product/productId: 6302468027 | review/userId: A1JKFUUCZRA3Z4 | review/summary: Two stories about female bonding | review/text: It was a joy watching Evelyn (Kathy Bates) transforming from an emotional eater to someone wanting to take better care of herself.  Evelyn is a sweet and kind woman, but shows she has a more feisty side in the very funny parking lot scene.<br />It was also a joy watching the relationship between Evelyn and Mrs. Threadgoode (Jessica Tandy) develop.<br />Their relationship provided comic relief and a brighter light that shone over the darker main story.<br /><br />The main story involves two females, Idgy (Mary Stuart Masterson) and Ruth (Mary-Louise Parker) whose friendship began reluctantly and later turns into a best friendship.<br />While their friendship develops, it seems like Idgy is romantically courting Ruth. For example, there's a scene where they're both boarding a train and Idgy reaches her hand down (like a gentleman) to help delicate Ruth onto the train. In another scene, Idgy impresses Ruth by showing her how she can charm bees. When a shocked but charmed Ruth asks her why she did it, Idgy replies, "I did it just for you."<br /><br />A very sweet gesture, but also kind of a romantic, too. There's a scene where Idgy kisses Ruth on the cheek and although they don't make out or anything, it did imply Idgy might be a lesbian...especially since she also doesn't date men and also dresses like a man.<br />Whether the friendship is romantic or not, though, it's a strong one. These women go to great lengths to protect one another when they need it the most.<br /><br />Besides depicting friendship in this movie, slavery is also depicted. White people are shown as both cruel and loving towards slaves (with Idgy and Ruth being on the loving team). One thing that might upset people is seeing slaves depicted as happy slaves enjoying having a master. One slave even sings happily while he works.<br />There's a plot twist involving this same slave that is both clever and disgusting.<br /><br />This movie can be a little slow at times. I understand two simultaneous stories take time to develop, but I still thought the pacing could've been sped up a bit.<br />There were also some inconsistencies, too. For example, in one flashback, Idgy is a little girl and Ruth is a young woman. But in another flashback, both Idgy and Ruth look the same age.<br />Also, the ending implies that Mrs. Threadgoode was actually Idgy all along.  However, in the beginning, Mrs. Threadgoode announced herself as Idgy's sister-in-law...so either she's lying about being Idgy's sister-in-law or she's lying about being Idgy. The ending doesn't clear that up.<br /><br />Also, although Idgy is a genuinely good-hearted and brave person, she's also a smoker, a thief, and a prankster at church which makes it hard to consider her a role model.<br />But overall, though, I consider this a warm-hearted and clever movie.
