 | product/productId: 0792837118 | review/userId: ACIBQ6BQ6AWEV | review/summary: Landmark Musical Shows It's Age | review/text: There are basically two types of musical: the "show" or "classic" musical, in which a loose plot provides an excuse for musical numbers, and the "integrated" musical, in which the plot and musical numbers support each other.  The show musical was standard well into the twentieth century; even so, the shift toward the integrated musical began fairly early in the century, and surprisingly it was Hollywood that led the way.  Among the landmarks in this change was the 1933 HALLELUJAH I'M A BUM, which featured music by Rogers & Hart and which starred the most famous singer of the era, Al Jolson.<br /><br />The story is classic Great Depression nonsense.  While the rich, famous, and powerful struggle with penthouse difficulties, the homeless are cheerful folk who bounce from meal to meal in happy fashion.  The result is a fantasy world in which a Central Park tramp (Jolson) and the Mayor of New York (Frank Morgan) can be friends and social equals.  When a misunderstanding occurs between the mayor and his girl (Madge Evans), the high society girl decides to throw herself off a bridge--and is rescued by the tramp.  The girl looses her memory in the fall, the tramp doesn't know who she is, and the frantic mayor doesn't know where she is.  Needless to say, much romantic and comic confusion ensues.<br /><br />Seen today, there is something intrinsically distasteful in the "happy hobo" construct, which has it that all these homeless folk are just as merry as you and I and don't actually want or need a roof over their heads.  But what makes HALLELUJAH I'M A BUM famous isn't the story line or even the performances: it's the way the movie handles the transition between script and song.  Instead of simply having the actors burst into song, the way is smoothed by a dialogue-like but distinctly musical patter.  It was a novel approach, and it would point the way to everything from THE WIZARD OF OZ to GIGI.  The script by S.N. Behrman is clever and witty, and director Louis Milestone is extremely innovative in his staging.  Yes, HALLELUJAH I'M A BUM was and is an extremely, extremely influential film.  On the other hand, it's not a greatly watchable one.<br /><br />The big problem is Al Jolson (1886-1950), who was easily the single most famous singer of his day.  Trouble was, Jolson was never able to find a way to translate himself to film: he instead plays exactly as if he is on the Broadway stage and has to reach the very last row of balcony seats.  The result is uncomfortably stagy, with lots of eye rolling and you-may-applaud-now moments.  It is incredibly tiresome.  The other performances are alternately tiresome (Harold Langdon) and merely acceptable (Morgan, Evans), the music isn't all that memorable, and in spite of the clever script and Milestone's speed-slick direction the whole thing feels stale.  To add insult to injury, the DVD picture and sound quality isn't all that great.  So, unless you're a hardcore fan who has to trace the roots of the American musical, you might want to give HALLELUJAH I'M A BUM a miss.<br /><br />GFT, Amazon Reviewer
