 | product/productId: 6300248550 | review/userId: A2DSXA1E02C86D | review/summary: An overwrought melodrama not my cup of tea | review/text: JANE EYRE is the latest in a series of film adaptations of 19th century novels by female English authors that I've been encouraged to view by female acquaintances curious as to my reaction to such genteel fare. While I've thoroughly enjoyed the screen versions of Austen's PRIDE AND PREJUDICE, SENSE AND SENSIBILITY, and MANSFIELD PARK, Charlotte Bronte's JE, I'm afraid, draws a line in the sand that I cannot cross. <p>This 1983 cinematic release of JE is, as I understand it, a faithful rendering of the original written work - a claim I have no desire to verify by reading the latter. In any case, Jane (Zelah Clarke) is an orphan, raised initially by an unloving benefactress and then in a school for girls, who at 18 comes to live at Thornfield Hall, the great house of Mr. Rochester (Timothy Dalton), where Jane is employed as governess to Rochester's illegitimate daughter. Both Jane and Rochester are extremely lonely individuals, and the course of their subsequent emotional relationship is overwrought and melodramatic to an extreme. The "thorn" in Thornfield is apt, especially as it relates to the dark secret which Rochester hides in a garret room. <p>One cannot fault the quality of the production or the acting, and I'll allow three stars in recognition. Clarke is superb as the somber but independent Jane whose emotions are continuously buffeted. Dalton is perfect as the darkly handsome and brooding Rochester. The costuming seems impeccable (though I'm in no expert position to judge). And the locations of the shoot, while gloomy, are at least in England, a green and otherwise pleasant land that is my spiritual home.<p>I loved Austen's P&P, S&S and MP for the wry and sometimes mischievous humor demonstrated by those stories' respective heroines. JANE EYRE lacks any humor whatsoever. It's unrelentingly dark, gloomy and depressing. Even the scene where Jane has her fortune told by the gypsy woman is not so much a crack in the dark tenor of the storyline as another one of Rochester's manic mood swings. One wishes Rochester would just snap out of it.<p>My opinion of JE is liable to be roundly excoriated by Bronte fans. That's fine. I still wouldn't recommend it unless one is seeking to come down precipitously from an emotional high. And with a run time 1 minute short of 4 hours, the agony seems endless.
