 | product/productId: 080012166X | review/userId: ANKFV6COYCJ98 | review/summary: Synthesis of a Rich Tradition | review/text: ...This movie was NOT meant to be a faithful rendition of the original novel by Bram Stoker ("Bram Stoker's Dracula" in the title notwithstanding.) Vampire lore owes a great debt to this...gothic novelist, but the movie had  more grandiose goals than mere mimicry. This movie is a synthesis of the various subplots, interpretations, lore and speculation that has flowered AROUND the novel over the years. This is the movie of the Dracula tradition, not a purist's adaption of the novel.<p>The departures from the novel are not mere eye candy meant to appeal to a modern audience. Debates about how effectively the eye candy appeals are irrelevant. This was not their purpose. These "departures" are powerful interpretations that have compelled so many viewers, readers, and thinkers that they have become part of the way  we "know" Dracula. People have been thinking about Dracula for years. This movie is a documentation of that thought.<p>Lucy's and Mina's highly sensual encounters with the Count are  largely accepted interpretations of the unsupervised and thus highly suspicious encounters in the novel. The addition of "topical" material, like early cinematographs in the background, delve into the social context of the novel. Stoker's characters are fascinated with new technology. This informs their hopes, just as the mysterious villain from the east threatens their civilization. The brief little dance between Mina and Van Helsing represents the valorous love, tinged with barely concealed sensuality and possessiveness, that motivates all the men who fight for "their girls." Dracula himself has had so many romantic and sexual fantasies strung about him over the years that his transformation into a "lover" in this film is hardly suspect. Yes, this is a departure from the text, but certainly not the tradition that has evolved around Stoker's compelling title character. <p>In all, this movie deserves kudos for taking on a rich and complex tradition rather than merely a novel. The fact that it manages to be beautiful and include so many quality performances is simply icing on the cake. The result is perhaps disjointed, but faithful in its goal.
 | product/productId: 6301969855 | review/userId: A3LU79BYMWZEW9 | review/summary: Deneuve of dat woman! | review/text: Visually, THE HUNGER is just about all you can ask for.  In terms of plot development, those who find it lacking make a very good point.  It could have been, you'll pardon the expression, fleshed out a bit more.  But it does have Deneuve and Bowie as elegant vampires--undead who are living the high life in '80s Manhattan.  It's chic, stylish fun, and we audience members are as curious and (many of us anyway) as seduced by it all as Susan Sarandon's character ultimately is.  The variations on the classic vampire story conventions (namely, as others have pointed out, that these vampires go out in the daylight, don't seem unduly afraid of garlic or crucifixes, and speak with elegant--not comic--European accents) make the film more intriguing than it otherwise might have been, but what we ultimately need in the absence of all the old vampire cliches is a new mythology to hang the story on.  That may have been articulated in Whitley Strieber's source novel, but it's largely missing from the film.  There's something vague about Egyptian gods being at the root of it all.  OK, so how did this Nile Delta vampirism wend its way to Deneuve's France and/or Bowie's England?.  How did they meet, and just what was the nature of the 200 year old love story prior?  What makes her choose Bowie (then), or Sarandon (now) as a consort and not just another victim?  Why does the aging process, staved off for centuries, suddenly overtake Bowie with a vengeance, and why don't his (despearate?) killings of at least two young victims even begin to reverse the process?  Why Why Why?  Well, apparently the filmmakers did not want to burden us with all that detail.  They knew damn well that we'd be there for the elegant decadence and, of course, those equally elegant love scenes between Deneuve and Sarandon.  Worth the price of admission certainly.  Worth the price of purchasing the film in any currently available format?  Well, that's up to you, of course.  Me, I doubt I'll hanker to see THE HUNGER more than once more in my lifetime.  So as long as they have rentals, I'm good.  You, however, may choose to revive it more frequently.  In which case, you'll doubtless find is as collectible as Deneuve's Miriam finds her ghastly consorts.
