 | product/productId: 0790744945 | review/userId: AIY4H4KWR2KWZ | review/summary: Shocked At The Genuine Chemistry | review/text: This came up as a queue suggestion based on previous rentals, so I admit to being very surprised. There's no way I would've randomly chosen to screen this film, none. Primarily because of the cast - more specifically the female lead. And like so many questionable casting decisions which, not only raise eyebrows, but typically equate to box office demise, the pairing of Jimmy Cagney and Bette Davis is fairly pronounced considering their differing personalities and respective careers.<br /><br />Like him or not, when you order Cagney, you know more or less what you're getting. The chance element for me was putting money down on Ms. Davis - I'm not at all a fan, so that was a huge personal red flag.<br /><br />But curiosity got the better of me and I'm stunned to say that I truly enjoyed the film. This is a genuinely fun romantic adventure, not quite '<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001GUYAZY">It Happened One Night</a>', but very good nonetheless.<br /><br />Not surprised the see the Brothers Epstein (Julius & Irving) of 'Casablanca' fame having put their magic touch to the script.<br /><br />Again, I'm shocked at the genuine chemistry between the two leads. Ms. Davis acted her role to near perfection. I'm so used to her cool, enigmatic and potentially malevolent performances, that her turn at an ingenue was refreshing to say the least. Her spirited, and dare I say it, sexy energy really came through. Wow. :-D<br /><br />I had absolutely no idea she could do this type of work. And I'm sad to note that after watching this film, I spent quite a bit of time and effort into looking into her earlier works in the hopes of recapturing the magic of this performance - there are none. As far as I can tell, 'Bride' was singularly unique; the only time Davis actually played the sweet spunky young woman caught up in the romance of adventure and high spirit.<br /><br />As I originally feared, the bulk of her career was formed around a harsh core of cynicism and deviousness. Of course I will always appreciate her skill at doing those characters; we all need the great dark personas in order to truly craft excellence in film - without the dark you can never understand and appreciate the light. But it seems like she lost something along the way, her 'Joan Winfield' character hints at a career that might've been fascinating and entertaining on a completely different path.<br /><br />'Bride' is a genuinely fun romantic comedy - and if you enjoyed 'It Happened' - you'll enjoy this fun film.  &lt;nod><br /><br />Movie Rant: How pathetic is it that today's filmmakers have lost this storytelling ability?<br /><br />I've given up hope that the cookie-cutter film school grads being pushed out today, like so many strands of smelly Play-Doh, can recreate this kind of flick. At this juncture, I no longer care if they do a complete and total ripoff -  plot, screenplay, script, set design, lighting, cinematography, character names - just redo the whole shebang and slap your name onto the project. I just want a modern version of this kind of film with today's stars. Had such high hopes for 'The Bounty Hunter', especially with the always enjoyable Gerard Butler as the grungy male lead. That should've been an easy slam dunk, but...<br /><br />There seems to be some kind of massive brain-lock across the industry when it comes to doing these types of productions anymore. My fear is that it's a generational defect. Like when you copy a copy, it's not quite as sharp. If you do it repeatedly, eventually what's produced is illegible. I believe we might be witnessing decades of sliding standards, a lowering of the bar - not just in films but culturally - we're experiencing the result of Idiocracy In Action.
