 | product/productId: 0800130936 | review/userId: A6VXZ1EEPRTLV | review/summary: Michael Bay's investment yields huge dividends... | review/text: Producers Don Simpson and Jerry Bruckheimer (Beverly Hills Cop, Days Of Thunder, Top Gun), known for a slick over the top approach to action, are behind Bad Boys (1995), a big and loud extravaganza teaming Martin Lawrence and Will Smith, as Miami police detectives on the trail of millions in stolen cash and drugs.  Michael Bay (The Rock, Armageddon, Pearl Harbor, Transformers) makes his directorial debut, in this action/comedy, that sort of delivers in the action department, but not so much when it comes to laughs.<br /><br />A gang led by a criminal named Fouchet (Tcheky Karyo), engineers the audacious robbery of millions of dollars of confiscated drugs from the police evidence vault.  During the robbery, one of the team takes a bag of drugs for personal use, and arranges to party with a couple of women in a hotel.  Fouchet arrives, and eliminates his greedy collaborator and one of the ladies, but Julie Mott (Tea Leoni) manages to escape a hail of bullets, by jumping from a roof into a swimming pool.<br /><br />Rich playboy Mike Lowery (Smith), and dedicated family man Marcus Burnett (Lawrence) are Miami police detectives assigned to work on this most crucial of cases.  Lowery isn't in the office when Julie calls police headquarters, so Burnett impersonates him, and arranges to meet her.  Fouchet's men are close behind, shooting up Julie's apartment, as she and Burnett barely escape to safety with her two pet dogs.  Mott refuses to enter protective custody, so Burnett stashes her at his partner's apartment.  Burnett's boss Captain Howard (Joe Pantoliano), noisily orders him continue to impersonate Lowery, and get vital information from Julie.  Burnett moves into Lowery's bachelor pad, while Lowery takes up residence in Burnett's home with his wife Theresa (Theresa Randle) and two kids.<br /><br />Much of the remainder of the film is centered on keeping Julie believing that Burnett is actually his free-wheeling partner.  It's a fairly ridiculous situation, as Julie is certainly intelligent enough to handle the truth.  The elaborate charade provides some rather forced and predictable, low level humor.  Lawrence has fairly good chemistry with Smith, who mostly plays the straight man to Lawrence's goofing.  Bad Boys tries hard to be funny, but isn't very successful, despite Lawrence being an accomplished ad libber.  Tea Leoni, as the sharp tongued Julie, seems too bright to be involved in most of the goofiness, and at times seems out of place with her co-stars.<br /><br />The DVD commentary by Michael Bay is highly informative, though sporadic at points.  The director repeatedly states that the studio did not believe in the film, and that he was working under extreme pressure, on a very limited budget, with his directorial future at stake.  Bay says that he even paid the studio out of his own pocket, to shoot a particular scene.  Bay also relates some interesting anecdotes about stars Lawrence and Smith.  Of particular interest is the amount of improvisation that was apparently done, as apparently there were some big problems with the script.  Bay often focuses on the pressure of meeting shooting schedules, and budgetary concerns, but his investment and efforts certainly did pay off.  Bad Boys went on to make over 100 million dollars in profits, and Michael Bay has become one of Hollywood's most in demand directors.<br /><br />A fast paced film with good production values and a cartoonish plot, Bad Boys largely delivers what you might expect from a Simpson/Bruckheimer production.  With Smith and Lawrence trading barbs, this surprise performer at the box office helped launch Will Smith's movie career.  It would be followed by the more explosive and exciting, Bad Boys II in 2003.
