 | product/productId: 0792844580 | review/userId: A1LQLQUJJZUBTC | review/summary: Ravishing Cinematography & No Need to Apologize | review/text: I've probably watched BLACK NARCISSUS a dozen times, quite a few at special screenings in a theatre, others on TV, VHS & a couple DVDs. I agree with others who wrote that this blu-ray version is best--and I didn't play it on a blu-ray machine. Now that I realize how overly emotional Amazon reviews can be (yes, I've been guilty too), I really didn't plan to reply to what I way overboard 1 star reviews. However, a couple issues were raised that I really feel a need to respond. 1. BLACK NARCISSUS is somehow anti-Catholic and/or anti-nun. 2. The movie is colonialist for not having been filmed on location. 1. The nuns are probably Anglican & I think a fair-minded person would fail to see anything anti-nun or anti-religious. 2. In 1948 hardly ANYBODY filmed on location. This is a British film & Britain was still recovering from a particularly economically devastating World War. If this isn't enough, the idea of location shooting in the Himalayas in 1948 is ludicrous. For one thing, the production company would never have secured the necessary affordable insurance to proceed. The only expression of colonialist idealogy are expressed by the nuns & particularly Sister Ruth who seems to hate everybody. British nuns were as deeply prejudice as their fellow countrymen, naturally they would express these feelings. In fact, the film demonstrate that it's the nuns, not the common folk, who are seriously out of touch with the local reality. That's all I have to say. Other reviewers have appropriately commented on this beautifuil film. I'm adding a few images & I hope people enjoy them & may be motivated to watch BLACK NARCISSUS & judge its merits for themselves.
