 | product/productId: 0780631153 | review/userId: A25FDX17O3QKLT | review/summary: "Have you ever been struck by lightning? It hurts" | review/text: Magnolia is one of those wonderful films that goes beyond the<br /><br />normal boundaries of film. Surprisingly the closest thing I can compare it to is the black and white D. W. Griffith classic 'Intolerance".<br /><br />What Kubrick's Lolita did to have the viewer not just watch but experience paranoia, Magnolia does the same for the experience of synchronicity.<br /><br />The movie is long but more than worth the time invested.<br /><br />A number of stories are woven together. The movie has a definite point but does not preach. Instead it sucks you into to its reality with a pacing worthy of Kubrick's Barry Lyndon. Rather than turn this review into a Kubrick lovefest I mention Barry Lyndon because of the masterful way the director slowed down the pace of the modern world to draw the viewer into the world of Thackary's Lyndon. Unlike Barry Lyndon though even though both movies are on the long side the pacing of Magnolia is far from slow.<br /><br />Through the story of a number of stories in Magnolia we experience a whole new out look into the ordinary world, seeing it as a type of hyper-world, and after the movie we are left with the feeling that the world is not so ordinary after all.<br /><br />The idea that our lives are interconnected is not a new one. However it is the subject of "coincidence" that is the predominant one. All of us have at one time or another experienced a coincidence. But what if our world was made up of a series of "coincidences" that had a logic to them. Call them a layers of rhythms that existence beyond our perceptions, call them synchronicity, call them the hand of God, in this movie we are prodded into experiencing ever so gently and with more than a little humor is that something is going on.<br /><br />This is not a conspiracy of nations or shadowy groups we find ourselves commonly seeing in many of today's movies but conspiracies of the universe. And it is not a necessarily disinterested synchronicity in play as there is definitely a touch of karma at play and in the end redemption. The true art of this movie is that we are not told a story we experience it.<br /><br />To summarize the story is to not do it justice however I offer this brief synopsis.<br /><br />The movie is begun with a narator telling the story of three strange incidents in history and then the story begins.<br /><br />  A famous powerful ancient TV game show producer, Earl Partridge, is dying-his death is eminent. He made his fortune in a game show that exploited brainy children. His young wife is addicted to drugs and racked with guilt. Meanwhile Partridge's caring but somewhat emotionally fragile male nurse trys frantically to contact Partridge's son, who is the misogynistic leader of a cult like self improvement group dedicated to taking advantage of women and who disowned his father long ago. Partridge's game show heir, Jimmy Gator, continues the show. He too is dying of cancer. The part of the wreckage of lives Partridge and Gator leave in their wake is the now over the hill Whiz-kid Donnie Smith (played magnificently by William H. Macy) and the current Whiz kid Stanley. All both Stanley and Donnie want is to be loved. In the meantime Gator's daughter, a victim of her father's abuse , attempts to finally have a normal relationship with someone who is caring and human. As twisted as this plot sounds even more twists are revealed.<br /><br /> Although this may sound somewhat like a soap opera it is far from superficial and along with revealing a hyper-real vision of the world in which we live tackles such issues as forgiveness, redemption and damnation without sounding like a Christian sermon. It is what Robert Anton Wilson called "chapel perilous". You may never be the same after seeing this film.<br /><br />The sound track by Aimee Mann greatly adds to the movie.<br /><br />"The book says, we might be through with the past, but the past ain't through with us."<br /><br />  Weird, wise and wonderful.
