 | product/productId: 6301103491 | review/userId: AL1XGMQHKBQPV | review/summary: Don't judge a book (video) by it's cover | review/text: Back in the early 90's I've seen Sleepaway Camp on the shelves at the local video store. It looked like a typical Friday the 13th slasher knockoff, a genre which I was tired of, a killer stalking kids at a summercamp? Not too original, guys. I was more into the Nightmare on Elm Street and Hellraiser, films that were more rooted into the supernatural. So with a stick up my butt, I passed. In the recent months I've been buying up dvd's of horror and exploitation films I've heard of or neglected to see. Well, Sleepaway Camp was on the list, so with an open mind and some low (very low) expectations, I gave it a look. I'm still kicking myself for being so ignorant. Sleepaway Camp is a good if not underated, horror film with a great shock ending. I wouldn't rank it up with the films of Hitchcock, De Palma, or Argento, but it definitly deserves an honorable mention. The image of Angela at the closing of the film will stay with you for a awhile. Aside from that it is a low budget affair with some campy acting, but I was expecting that and actually enjoyed it. The filmwork itself was of a better quality than I expected. Anyone wanting to explore the genre of the 80's slasher film, this a must see!
