 | product/productId: 0792844017 | review/userId: A3V5OR76MAFDMJ | review/summary: Decent Film But Shamelessly Revisionist | review/text: This movie is not awful, and the plot, musical score and acting performances are in many cases quite decent.  However, it contains a wildly inaccurate, revisionistic depiction of the political affiliations of the  various Yugoslav guerrillas.<p>First, the movie depicts the CHETNIKS as  pro-German.  NOTHING could be further from the truth.  The Chetniks were  anti-Communist, pro-Allied officers (led by Draza Mihailovic) who fought  against the Wehrmacht in an attempt to restore the Yugoslav monarchy and  the duly constituted government overthrown by the Germans in 1941.  They  had a generally western political orientation and were predominantly Serb.  The USTASHE (headed by Ante Pavelic), on the other hand, were pro-Nazi and  anti-Chetnik.  They were overwhelmingly made up of Croatian nationalists  and fought alongside the German army against the Chetniks and the Allies  throughout the 1941-45 Yugoslav campaign.<p>The Communist PARTISANS  (fronted by Josip Broz Tito) were pro-Soviet.  Although Tito was a Croat,  the partisans were principally Serb and fought against both the Chetniks  and the Ustashe.  They were far more reckless than the Chetniks in their  fight against the Germans, and as a result their tactics invited the  typically bloody German reprisals against the Yugoslav people as a whole.  At the end of the war, the partisans turned their (Soviet supplied) arms  against the Chetniks in a civil war against the Yugoslav government and  brutally communized the war-weary nation, executing Mihailovic shortly  afterward.  The present-day Serbian government of Slobodan Milosevic is the  ideological heir of Tito, and the often savage events in the Balkans since  June 25, 1991 serve to prove how intolerant these people are against any  group who seeks freedom, peace and independence from Belgrade.<p>Since even  a casual student of WW2 knows the distinction between these groups, the  only logical conclusion that can be drawn is that the makers of this movie  (which must have been reviewed by and acceptable to Yugoslavia's Communist  government in 1978) purposely sought to distort the truth.<p>By maligning  the Chetniks in such a manner, this movie does a disservice to all Balkan  peoples - as well as to the Allied soldiers who fought alongside them in  WW2.  If this film were edited and every use of the word  &quot;Chetnik&quot; was replaced by &quot;Ustashe&quot;, then this  injustice would be properly dealt with.
