 | product/productId: 6302229928 | review/userId: ANCOMAI0I7LVG | review/summary: Much more than tongue and cheek... | review/text: Jiri Menzel's `Ostre Sledovane Vlaky' has been heralded as one of the definitive films of the 60's, a deliciously engrossing `coming of age' story that mixes enough humor with drama to create a beautifully complete depiction of life.  It reminds me somewhat of `Lasky Jedne Plavovlasky' and the brilliant `Le Souffle au Coeur' in that it uses natural adolescent curiosity to elaborate on even deeper and more mature revelations.<br /><br />In `Ostre Sledovane Vlasky' we are introduced to young Milos.  Milos is a young, nave virgin.  I want to make something clear.  One particular reviewer accused this movie of being nothing more than an exploitive message to viewers that promiscuity is acceptable and expected.  That is not the case.  This film doesn't endorse this action (the character of Josef alone somewhat shows a condemning attitude towards this course) but it simply uses it as a way to explore the insecurities and very real fears of adolescence.  Young men especially are raked with these very curiosities, and the feeling of inadequacy, especially in the intimacy department, can scare a man for life.  `Ostre Sledovane Vlasky' merely uses this avenue of life to serve as a foundation for deeper character development.  I just felt the need to say that, since this reviewers ignorance irritated me.  So, back to the movie.  Milos is young and questioning his ability to perform (as a man).  The thing is, his insecurities run deeper than a mere intimacy problem, but he's not really aware of anything else at his young age.  Taken under the wing of middle-aged rebel (and ladykiller) Hubicka, Milos gets a crash course in the ways of love, which he attempts to use on the beautiful Masa.<br /><br />Yes, there is a political turn in the film towards the end, which I won't elaborate on so as not to ruin anything for the viewer, but I will say that this point is one that the reviewer I mentioned failed to notice.  This turn of events (which he claimed as pointless) is the crux of the film, for it shows how the director's use of intimacy was merely a mask for greater things.<br /><br />The acting here is astonishing, especially from the supporting players.  That isn't to say that Vaclav Neckar isn't wonderful as young Milos, but Josef Somr and Jitka Scoffin are just brilliant.  Somr especially takes a very despicable character and makes him likable and enjoyable.  Despite the fact that the actions taken by Hubicka are at times reprehensible, the charismatic way in which he carries them out (that stamp scene is just marvelous) make him delightful almost.  Scoffin is far more than a pretty face here (she is stunning), for she uses a mixture of restrained sensuality and nave awkwardness to flesh out the object of Milos' affections.<br /><br />With a cheeky humor that makes the more serious aspects of the film stand out, `Ostre Sledovane Vlasky' is a must see for any fan of foreign film, coming of age stories or humorous splices of human drama.  It is a beautiful and sincere film that lives up to the hype.
