 | product/productId: 6301008723 | review/userId: AYMZTWBG0V53W | review/summary: A terrific treatment indeed... | review/text: Hmmm, my oh my, "The Exorcist" film version is a strange one. First off, and it might be trivial at this point to mention it, the film version is very loosely based upon the novel itself. Friedkin's film is an agnostic treatment of this subject matter, not a truly belief-based interpretation. Even though the director put back in some of the missing "carpentry" (as Blatty refers to) in the "Version You've Never Seen", there are still a great deal of unexplained questions. This movie is not really about the occult all that much; it is more of a family-in-crisis kind of drama, with a lot of religious overtones tossed in. The novel includes scenes that make the threat of the supernatural more understandable to the reader (in the film, Chris has no book on occult lore laying around the house, the medium who showed up at her party warning her to take the "toy" away from Regan, the sub-plot about Karl's daughter, etc. have all been stripped away for this abbreviated film interpretation). In the film, things happen in far too abrupt fashion, with scenes of blasphemy mixed in with scenes of spiritual faith, none of which ever gels completely. Also, as one reviewer on here stated before, Blatty has not really done his best to tell a cohesive story. It appears that there is a battle between good and evil going on, but the old Jesuit priest's conflict with the demon is perhaps one of the most mis-understood pyschological Western-type motifs ever committed to celluloid (everybody keeps referring to the entity as "the Devil," or "Satan", not the real character shown in statue form in the movie). Friedkin's film is far more empathetic to the plight of Chris, and this is no doubt a strong feminist movie (despite poor Linda's abusive scenes) in the director's hands. Therefore, we end up with a movie that is entirely humanist, but no less fascinating (and superbly entertaining, in my opinion, at least). This is not a detective movie, either, despite the brilliant Lee J. Cobb's thankless role. Finally, as for this being a horror film, I ultimately have to disagree with this conclusion...there is nothing here that has the INTENTION to frighten viewers as much as it does to make a viewers THINK, and therefore it is more dramatic (I admit quite intense at times) than scary. One reason this film will stand the test of time (so to speak) and keep fascinating viewers today who might be new to it is simply for the reason that, unlike most of today's scare pictures, this one is about age old ideas concerning themes that we all have some steak in (life and death, c'mon) and a set of terrific performances from every actor involved, despite the thin storyline that they were given to work with, they really bring these performances home in a unique fashion (Miller is intensely good here, but so are Von Sydow, Burstyn, sweet Linda, etc.) Anyway, this movie also has some funny moments that I believe to be intentional (the phone ringing while Karras is listening to the tape comes to mind).<br />As for this BluRay presentation, one could not ask for better. Every extra that any sane person could wish for is here, and the picture and sound are superlative. Earth-shakingly good effects, sound design, etc. After "The Exorcist", I think the horror film underwent a dramatic revision in terms of the use of sound effects and music, as the old "jump out of your seat" music that informed you that a scene would be terrifying (like in "Psycho") would no longer be so obviously, or so routinely, used ever again. I was fortunate enough to see the 2000 extended cut at a local theater a couple of years back on Halloween night, and the experience of watching a good classic movie like this one is always more rewarding than watching these simplistic newer movies that we have nowadays. I enjoy the expanded cut more so because to me it is, in a sense, the most complete version (despite some silly effects shots that really shouldn't have been added). This movie should be a lesson to all of those who wish to make films...effects are always important, but the major special effects are always the actors and the script itself, not the visuals.
