 | product/productId: 6300183297 | review/userId: A1ABDWJU9RTUWU | review/summary: Youth Passing into Manhood | review/text: Rumble Fish opens with an image of the sky over a town, whose time-elapsed features morph as time passes before our eyes, so that we know that the story to follow takes place at a point in this infinite pool of days. The black and white cinematography, leather jackets and sneering star suggest that we are watching a film from the 50's, a forgotten contemporary of Blackboard Jungle or Rebel Without a Cause; then the realization slowly seeps in that this dress, this attitude, define not an era of history but adolescence. Adolescence, when the scales are lifted from our eyes, and we see hypocrisy everywhere. An hypocrisy that fades into conventionality as we become older and unwilling conspirators. What once seemed certain evil now seems reasonable and necessary. But for that brief space of time, never captured again, we see things with a clarity  that makes us the ultimate outsiders.<br /><br />Such is the fate of Rusty James, who romanticizes his outsider status and whose identity revolves around his idol, the god-like Motorcycle Boy. As the film progresses the character reaches his epiphany, and his innocence is revealed for the illusion it really is, an illusion in a world of illusion. However, with the revelation comes the haunting remembrance of that dim dream of indestructability - like the fighting fish that give the film it's title, a captive of his ignorance of the outside world.<br /><br />Dillon is brilliant in portraying this vulnerable toughness, and the growth from the narcissism of youth to the tragic resignation of a mature person. Moving and profound, this expertly directed film deserves a wider viewership.
