 | product/productId: 078881107X | review/userId: A30JPZ9TZ7I61U | review/summary: Possibly the cutest cat voice ever (the Japanese version)! | review/text: Just putting in my two cents here:<br /><br />I have viewed this in the two English dub versions as well as the original Japanese.  I must say that the original Japanese is the best of the three by far.  I enjoy foreign films and anime, so I am used to hearing films in their original dialogue.  The actor who voices Jiji is absolutely amazing (in the Japanese version), the perfect mix of wit, sarcasm, narcissism, and cuteness.<br /><br />The film is one of Miyazaki's more lighthearted pieces.  You won't find boar demons or sky pirates or evil wizards casting curses here.  Though on the surface it does appear simple and heartwarming, there is a bit more to it than that.  Kiki grapples with coming to age and understanding her witchy powers.  As with most Miyazaki films, the heroine is rather ordinary looking but possesses strength and courage and a kind heart.  She is well liked by those she meets and often performs good deeds.  This creates an instantly likable protagonist, with whom the viewer sympathizes.  Add to this an interesting cast (although the Waldo look alike kid gets kind of annoying at times!), and you have the recipe for a wonderful feel-good film.<br /><br />Though Disney casts these films well for the English track, I still think it best to at least watch the original Japanese version of these films at least once.  Though Spirited Away, Princess Mononoke, and Howl's Moving Castle (with the exception of Christian Bale) have better English tracks than the English dubs on other Miyazaki films.<br /><br />This is certainly as good and lighthearted a film as My Neighbor Totoro and deserves a viewing by any Miyazaki fan.  I am an adult (no kids) and I still love his films.<br /><br />Also recommended: My Neighbor Totoro, Spirited Away<br />Recommended but a little more grown up themes: Princess Mononoke, Castle in the Sky, Howl's Moving Castle, Nausicaa
 | product/productId: 6302420458 | review/userId: A27QLYGAM9AU3M | review/summary: Wow!!!  What a film! | review/text: I'm not sure if people remember just how groundbreaking the editing on this film really was back in '91, but this is an enthralling 3.5 hour overview of the major questions that D.A. Jim Garrison raised about the Kennedy Assassination in his book &quot;On The Trail of the Assassins.&quot;  This film is a tour-de-force by Oliver Stone, and was very controversial for mixing new footage with real archived film clips in a way that many felt would only mislead the uninformed.  They have a point - some details of the arguments here don't hold up to careful scrutiny (truly interested persons should check out other sources, such as Gerald Posner's &quot;Case Closed&quot;) but the amazing thing about this film is that in just a few hours, it gives an amazingly rich &quot;crash course&quot; in the controversies surrounding the assassination investigation.  It successfully conveys Garrison's point of view as a well-intentioned professional who descends from a normal sense of early-60s civic pride into a multi-year journey of doubt about U.S. democracy, and anxiety regarding social changes.  The Cold War, Cuban Missile Crisis and Vietnam, political unrest and assassinations of the 60s...  This is a truly impressive film at relating one man's loss of civic faith, even if you disagree completely with the premises it explores.  It is loaded with stars and cameo appearances.  It can be enjoyed (or studied) again and again.  Particularly notable on the DVD is an interview with Fletcher Prouty, the real version of the film's &quot;Mr. X&quot; that encouraged and guided Garrison's suspicions.  Gary Oldman gives a completely knockout performance as Lee Harvey Oswald, and in my opinion this film also contains the best performance I've seen from Kevin Costner!  Surely only its controversy kept this from Best Picture Oscar possibilities.  What an amazing piece of filmmaking!  And the entire film is contained on one disc, too!
