 | product/productId: 6301338057 | review/userId: A1JH5J1KQAUBMP | review/summary: Serious, fascinating & flawed--but not blasphemous | review/text: This film is a serious, respectful exploration of Christ's dual nature from director Martin Scorcese and screenwriter Paul Schrader.  Here Christ (Willem Dafoe) is fully human, susceptible to all the weaknesses and temptations of man, tormented by his communications with God, which he does not at first understand.  In the beginning, his behavior bears all the symptoms of a man suffering from brain damage or a mental illness--seizures, pain, hallucinations.  Soon, however, he begins to perform miracles and gather disciples, chief among whom is Judas (Harvey Keitel), whose relationship with Jesus is a fascinating revision of what we know of him from the Bible.<br /><br />The power of Scorcese's film is undercut by some pretty serious miscalculations.  Although Dafoe is excellent, much of the cast appears to consist of New York method actors who do not inhabit the time and place of the story convincingly.  The appearance of David Bowie (in the small but significant role of Pontius Pilate) tore me right out of the film.  Peter Gabriel is an excellent musician, but his score, which blends Middle Eastern motifs with rock rhythms and electric guitar, was also a distraction.  In addition, there is a staginess to many of the settings.  Nevertheless, it's definitely worth a look.
