 | product/productId: 6302054230 | review/userId: AYQY3RB33F4J6 | review/summary: Arguably their most famous film | review/text: "Monty Python's Life of Brian" is one of the four film collaborations by the British comedy team resposible for the iconic sketch-comedy show "Monty Python". The other films are the medieval parody of "Monty Python and the Holy Grail", the riotous "Monty Python's Meaning of Life" and the compilation of sketches "And Now for Something Completely Different". Of these, "Brian" is possibly the most famous film.<br /><br />The plot, inasmuch as it really matters in a comedy, deals with a young man born in a stable in Roman-occupied Palestine. No, not that famous young man who went on to found a major world religion, another young man, albeit one who inadvertently finds himself with a stream of zealous followers.<br /><br />A plot like this will obviously risk being called blasphemous and sacriligeous, but the Python crew manage to tread just on the right side of religious objections while still taking part in one of the funniest films ever made.<br /><br />There are of course a number of very famous scenes here. One of these is the dialogue among the locals overhearing the Sermon on the Mount and misinterpreting one of the beatitudes as "blessed are the cheesemakers", a scene very closely followed by a visit to a stoning. Here, John Cleese plays an official in classic style, charging a man with blasphemy (although his only crime was to say that his wife's dinner was "fit for Jehovah"). The request that no stones be thrown "even if anyone says 'Jehovah'" is one of the many catchphrases known to comedy fans the world over.<br /><br />In due course, young Brian (Graham Chapman) falls in with a band of rebels trying to overthrow the Roman state. At least, they would be doing that if they could stop their political squabbles.  In order to escape from certain death, Brian must masquerade as a prophet - of whom, true to history, there are many. Despite not being a particularly talented prophet, he is ascribed a number of miracles and eventually crucified.<br /><br />The film is, however, more successful as a result of the Python comedy - which can be better appreciated when this is viewed as a series of vaguely linked sketches. The debates among the rebels are a real highlight, as are Brian's attempts at prophethood and the significance given to mundane events by his band of followers.<br /><br />This is also the film in which several iconic scenes take place. One of these is the shout of Brian's mother to an assembled multitude that "He's not the messiah! He's a very naughty boy", followed soon after by Brian's call that "You are all individuals", to which the crowd responds in one voice "Yes, we are all individuals" (Cleese then pipes up "I'm not!"). Another is the scene in which the words "Romans go home" is being written in Latin on a wall. A centurion catches the vandal and forces him to conjugate the sentence correctly, much in the style of Latin teachers of the day.<br /><br />The next classic moment is Pilate and his speech impediment of not being able to pronounce the letter R ("Welease Weginald") and his claim that the names "Biggus Dickus" and "Incontinentia Buttox" are quite normal ones for his friends to have.<br /><br />Of course, as most of the world knows, this is also the film in which - at the end of the crucifixion scene - the condemned men sing the immortal "Always Look On the Bright Side of Life".<br /><br />Is it blasphemous? Speaking as a history student, I find it hard to say that it is. For all the unique events surrounding the birth of Christianity, claims of prophethood and eventual crucifixion were quite common at the time in question.<br /><br />Is it as great as history records? Probably not. By all means it is an incredibly funny film, but it seems to have dated slightly more than the rest of the Python oevre. The Latin-teacher scene (Romane ite domum) is a prime example, as the humour can only really be appreciated with knowledge that this is the way dead languages were taught - and that dead languages were very popular at the time the film was made.<br /><br />That said, "Life of Brian" is definitely a landmark in British comedy and would not be out of place in anyone's DVD collection.
