 | product/productId: 0790741970 | review/userId: A1YDDQ6YCN678K | review/summary: Director Hugh Hudson's Best Film | review/text: I've always thought "Chariots of Fire" was an over-rated bore, and "Greystoke" was an incongruously stuffed-shirt version of an enjoyable pulp source. But in "Revolution", Hugh Hudson had a canvas that was well-suited to his sumptuous visuals. This is one of the best looking films I've seen. The 1770's may well have looked and felt the way this film looks and feels. Kubrick and Terence Malick (referenced by Hudson in the extras) really did come to mind when I first saw this years ago. And now, in retrospect, Michael Mann's "Last of the Mohicans". Or Ridley Scott's historicals.<br /><br />Strangely, like the later (ironically titled?) "The Patriot" (or the earlier Civil War film "Shenandoah") the protagonist gets involved in the conflict mainly because of his son, rather than idealism. The big issues that led to America's independence must be hard to present cinematically.  A fault of both films is the caricature villainy of the British military. Shorthand for myriad abuses of the colonists, I suppose.<br /><br />Criticisms of Pacino's accent are all based on what, exactly? First hand knowledge of Eighteenth Century dialects in a multi-cultural colonial region? As for the "muddled storytelling", the new Pacino narration added for the Revisited release adds some context, and, just as importantly, another layer of dramatic effect. Admirable that the star and director came back to this project after decades to try to improve its unjustly bad rep. Sadly, to me, one of the few scenes that Hudson eliminated was my favorite shot of the whole film: a really long tracking shot that must have been a pain to set up, but was apparently in service of a scene imposed by the studio that Hudson disagreed with, so out it came when he got the chance. Now I have to look for earlier home versions of the film (I'd been waiting years for a letterboxed release) to make sure I'm remembering that scene correctly. Anyone know if there's a widescreen disc or tape of the original theatrical version?
