 | product/productId: 0800116917 | review/userId: A30OXD42ZFYZLO | review/summary: Magnificent epic of an enigmatic person | review/text: David Lean's epic "Lawrence of Arabia" is one of the best epics filmed for multiple reasons: acting, photography, screenplay, music, direction, the list is endless. Filmed over 2 years is Morrocco and Jordan this brought together a spectacular cast to the tale of Col. T. E. Lawrence. Right from the moment in the start in the desert when the haunting music of Maurice Jarre shows the sunrise, one is mesmerised. It is difficult to produce such movies now. This is a cinematic masterpiece that defies imagination. Most important is the screenplay by Robert Bolt.<br /><br />Initially Lawrence thinks he can accomplish anything, however, he comes to realize the limits of his abilities. When he helps capture Damascus, Gen. Allenby realizes that he has no further use for him. He says "You are promoted Colonel now".<br /><br />Lawrence says "Why?".<br /><br />Prince Faisal says "Take the honor Colonel, be a little kind. Young men make wars and the virtues of war are the virtues of youth, courage and hope for the future. Then old men make the peace and the vices of peace are the vices of old men, mistrust and caution. It must be so."<br /><br />After Lawrence leaves and they start bargaining, at one point Prince Faisal says "Lawrence is a sword with two edges, we are both equally glad to be rid of him, are we not." Gen. Allenby says, "I thought that I was a hard man Sir." To this, Prince Faisal replies, "You are merely a general, I must be a king."<br /><br />Col. Brighton leaves in disgust over this. I do not think of any movie that has such a meaningful repartee. The passion and triumph shown in the movie is outstanding as are the bad parts. I would recommend this movie to any one interested in special movies, learning art of movies. It is not rated the AFI #5 for no reason. Peter O'Toole was outstanding in his first role. A classic in every sense of the word.
