 | product/productId: 0790732009 | review/userId: A2GYCEAZYQ0ZUY | review/summary: Enter the river at your peril | review/text: "Deliverance", John Boorman's harrowing depiction of a white water rafting expedition gone horribly wrong, was an Oscar nominee for best picture the same year as "The Godfather"(1972) and is, in some ways, a companion piece featuring a quartet engaged in male bonding. Instead of the ultimate crime family of three wildly disparate sons presided over by an immigrant patriarch, "Deliverance" offers up three suburban males following the misguided quest planned by a fourth,who is besotted with a half-baked sense of environmentalism and sure of his own macho capabilities. The role of Lewis offers Burt Reynolds a chance to play against the rowdy physicality of his previous roles, but the most complex and challenging role is owned by Jon Voight, midway between his Oscar nominated turns in "Midnight Cowboy"(1969) and "Coming Home"(1978). Voight evolves from a mild mannered fellow comfortable with his middle class existence to a bow and arrow wielding seeker of revenge for the death of one friend and the (spoiler alert) rape of another.<br />Set as it is deep in woods soon to be flooded in a dam building project, "Deliverance" shares some of the same concerns that would animate Boorman's "Emerald Forest"(1985), but instead of Amazonian natives whose very existence is in peril, this film gives us a gallery of threatening backwoods types, whose genetics are as inbred as their penchant for violence. The sole exception is the banjo playing boy whose digital wizardry in the "Duelling Banjos" scene with Ronnie Cox is the most memorable aural component of the film. Even the local sheriff, played by the author James Dickey, proves an unsettling presence, and not just because he seeks to uncover the truth behind the death of the Cox character.<br />The Blu-ray iteration of the film, released in 2007, is an early example of the species and probably the best version we're ever going to get. The source material reflects the era of its production with some muddy and overly saturated colors and obvious use of blue screen. Imperfect as it may be, "Deliverance" in Blu-ray still has the power to haunt. Who can forget "Duelling Banjos" or the dead arm reaching up from the water? This is no lady in the lake proffering Excalibur, but rather a reminder of how close supposedly civilized man is to his primitive ancestors who can be accessed both in dreams and in times of great stress.
 | product/productId: 630021625X | review/userId: A1TK6R2JSC97HL | review/summary: The triumph of the spirit - on ice. | review/text: This is an unforgettable mix of history and the study of human nature with supernatural overtones.  Peter Finch plays Nobile, the ill-fated Italian explorer who, years after a doomed 1928 expedition to overfly the North Pole in an airship, must confront the restless spirits of those whose lives were destroyed.  With his Roman apartment turned into a court of inquiry, Finch faces not only those killed when arctic winds tore his airship in half and split his crew up, but others whose lives were ruined by their loss, suffered from botched rescue attempts or otherwise suffered the horror of survival.  (The crew car of the dirigible "Roma" is torn clean from the main body of the airship, and those left in the now powerless gasbag on top can only look helplessly as they float away from their comrades.)  Among the accusers stands Nobile's fiercest rival, the legendary Roald Amundsen, (Sean Connery) and Claudia Cardinale as a crewmate's lover.  "Tent" excels because it rises above just telling the story of the expedition.  Instead, the film delves deeper into human nature, and the drama that men try to create.  (One unforgettable moment has Amundsen escaping the wreck of a plane in which he had planned to rescue his rival.  In a twist of fate, and to underline his own doom, Amundsen emerges from the ruined plane to discover the wreck of the Roma's main body and the now dead crewmembers who floated away with it.  Inside, he finds a bible opened to an ominous verse.  A fellow accuser chastises Amundsen - the found bible seems to have been a detail invented for dramatic purposes.  But this seems acceptable, since man needs some drama to highlight his own pitiful existnce.  Isn't that why men take to exploration in the first place?)  <p>Guilt isn't so much the issue, decides a surprisingly sympathetic Amundsen who lost his life in one of the rescue attempts.  Instead, Nobile cannot be punished for being no worse under the circumstances than his accusers who were, in turns, incompetent, greedy or unreasonably pious.  The last of these earns one of Nobile's ascetic accusers, Amundsen's harshest rebuke.  Piety, Connery says, is nice, but it's human nature to think for one's own pleasure.  If a man can't think for his own good he is less likely, not more, to think of the good of others.  Foregoing pleasure isn't pious, but sterile, and leaves only bitterness for the survivors.  "You should have given her one last night of pleasure" Amundsen concludes.  It is only after he discredits his fellow accusers that Amundsen offers what is both the most damning yet redeeming evidence: when boarding a rescue plane that can carry only him but not his crewmen off the ice-floe, the General thought not of his men's welfare, but of the warm bath that awaited him back in civilization.  <p>The "Red Tent" is in turns heart-breaking, incisive and also quite funny.  Finch is fun, but Connery runs the show (it's interesting to compare how he looks today and how he looks here, made up prematurely old).  The other characters are more one-note, but, like good leaders, Nobile and Amundsen are more than capable of putting their qualities together to form a complex whole.  A must-see.
