 | product/productId: 6301324382 | review/userId: A3T46X7M3AUDAB | review/summary: A flawed but fascinating diamond in the rough | review/text: You've seen this story many times before: strange & eccentric new kid enters school, he's possibly crazy & possibly gifted, befriended by that one understanding teacher, has a powerful & positive effect on his classmates.<br /><br />But this one is a little different, a little more daring.<br /><br />Most stories about gifted, rebellious outsiders make it clear from the very start that the hero deserves admiration & emulation. The good guys & bad guys are drawn in bold black & white lines, so that the viewer feels very comfortable identifying with the hero. This allows the viewer a vicarious & all-too-easy inner glow of satisfaction, even superiority, without any real risk.<br /><br />Again, this one is a little different.<br /><br />Rex Voorhaas is clearly eccentric, clearly gifted -- and clearly troubled as well. His Otherness has set him apart from the everyday, run-of-the-mill world, and that's enough to draw others toward him. In that respect, he's the classic rebellious hero & inspiration.<br /><br />But this story never makes it too comfortable for the viewer. Rex can be embarrassing, make the viewer squirm uncomfortably at times & wish that he'd just rein it in a bit, keep it acceptable & non-threatening for everyone. But he never does. He keeps the viewer guessing, on edge, not quite sure if he's truly gifted or just cracking up. Or is he both?<br /><br />That's what gives this small film such power, despite its rough corners & lack of cinematic polish. (And maybe those aren't necessarily flaws, either.) It doesn't make things easy for the viewer. It doesn't promise popularity & success for going against the norm -- if anything, it emphasizes that such actions may come at a higher price than most are willing to pay.<br /><br />Yet it's not warning us against nonconformity, either. There's no question that it approves of breaking through the numbed, narrow, mass-produced worldview that controls the lives of the majority. It just reminds us that such a breakthrough COSTS.<br /><br />The genuine individual is seldom applauded & celebrated while alive, although that often happens once the individual is safely dead, and thus easy to homogenize for the masses. More often, the genuine individual is marginalized, or crushed outright. But there's always room for those who become "individuals" according to the majority-approved rules of "individuality" ... just like all the hundreds of thousands exactly like them. The ones we see celebrated in the mass media. The safe ones.<br /><br />The ones who are nothing like the troubled, disturbing, compelling Rex Voorhaas.<br /><br />This unusual film isn't available on DVD, and the odds are that it never will be. But if you can find a copy, it's worth picking up. Rather than just reinforcing your cocoon of comfort, it'll make you uncomfortable & make you think. And that's a rare, valuable thing these days -- highly recommended!
