 | product/productId: 6300183092 | review/userId: A1YB29BIDULEYE | review/summary: Repressed Anger Is the True Horror | review/text: This review is dedicated to my friend Patricia who liked these werewolf movies. The movie starts with Larry Talbot (Lon Chaney Jr) returning to England after the death of his older brother. While we can sense that there had been some tension between Larry and his father (Claude Rains), things seem to be under control now. (Nonetheless, the point of repressed anger has begun.)<br /><br />Larry seems to be fitting in back in England, and he flirts with a shop owner named Gwen. She is reluctant, but she gives in and goes to a gypsy fair with him, along with her friend Jenny Williams. To some extent, Gwen is flattered by Larry's interest. But she is also engaged to Frank Andrews. (The gamekeeper at Claude Raines's estate.) This is when Jennie is attacked (seemingly by a wolf), and Larry runs to save her. Of course, Larry gets bitten, and poor Jenny was already killed.<br /><br />Certain parties suspect that Larry killed Jenny. While we (along with other characters) know he is innocent, we also know that this is just the start of Larry's problems. He does not become a werewolf right away, but we can see that he is having a difficult time controlling his rages now. (At one point, he looks like he is going to tear a group of women apart with his bare hands.) To be sure, they are unfairly blaming Gwen for Jenny's death; but still, Larry's sudden rage here is disturbing.<br /><br />Later, Larry runs into a gypsy. (The mother of the werewolf who attacked Jenny, and the werewolf Larry killed.) Larry does not want to believe that he will become a werewolf, but he can't entirely dismiss the possibility either. In a sympathetic moment, Larry becomes a werewolf, and we see that he has little (if any) control over his actions. Undoubtedly, this was someone's concept of a man suddenly losing control of his repressed anger.<br /><br />Larry wants to be cured, but what makes things difficult is that no one is really likely to believe his story, and he can not bring himself to  explain everything. (Tragic lack of communication.) An especially sad scene is when Larry gives his father a silver cane that can kill a werewolf.<br /><br />The climax is not only full of action, but there is a tragic twist that reminds us how ugly violence is. Overall, it's a great horror movie that explores the concepts of repressed anger.
