 | product/productId: 0780616456 | review/userId: A141IUB4JJPDB1 | review/summary: Red Harvest retold through Gun Poetry | review/text: As far as I know, this makes the second movie produced that's based on Dashiell Hammett's 'Red Harvest' (same guy who wrote The Thin Man and The Maltese Falcon). The first was Kurosawa's 'Yojimbo', which is undoubtedly a classic of Japanese cinema, itself spawning a revolution in American movie making when Sergio Leone began making all of Kurosawa's Samurai flicks into what we now know as Spaghetti Westerns.<br /><br />If you've seen Yojimbo, or its western rendition `A Fistful of Dollars', and enjoyed either one, then you should get quite a kick out of this Bruce Willis Powered send up to Hammett's first foray into grunge fiction. We already know the story (lonely town, gangs, double crossing, woman, money, gunfights, no good guy just bad guys and indifferent guys), so the delivery is what's going to make the movie.<br /><br />So how's the delivery? Absolutely Gun-alicious!<br /><br />The whole movie is quite visceral; the gun fights are reminiscent of John Woo (slightly unrealistic, but convincing) and the dialogue is retailored to match the characters delivery, whether it be quiet and whispered, loud and obnoxious, or just mumbles. Bruce Willis was the perfect choice for the lead, menacing and believable as always. My favorite casting choice was Christopher Walken, the great character actor of our generation. The humor and insanity he brought to `Last Man Standing' is what really tied the whole movie together, and earned it 5 solid stars.<br /><br />The Bottom Line: Know the history of this movie, and you'll enjoy it all the more.
 | product/productId: 6301773551 | review/userId: A2J00K3J9KPQD3 | review/summary: Great Movies- Star Wars (1977) | review/text: May 25, 1977 is the day that many people call the day that movies died, comparable to the day of Buddy Holly's death ("the day the music died"). This may be true, but George Lucas' "Star Wars" has been a classic ever since it first hit the silver screen. The brilliant use of special effects and adapting a classic story of good vs. evil has captivated "Star Wars" to become not just a great movie, but one of the most successful products in the history of the entertainment business.<br /> "Star Wars" is not necessarily about a story, since it is derived from multiple tales, but the movie itself is about how the story can be brought to its greatest. Taking much influence from Stanley Kubrick's "2001: A Space Odyssey", Lucas brought a new meaning to visual effects in film. But like Steven Spielberg's "E.T." or especially like "Who Framed Roger Rabbit", "Star Wars" was a technical watershed and a lot of fun at the same time.<br /> To watch "Star Wars" is not to just watch a movie. Watching "Star Wars" is being brought into the movie itself, which is extremely kind to its audience. It wants us to feel like Luke Skywalker as he dreams of adventure; or Han Solo, as the bad-boy smuggler who thinks himself all too cool; or Darth Vader, with enough power to strike terror into people's hearts; or at times we can feel like Obi-Wan Kenobi, who gives his knowledge of the Force and a lightsaber to Luke. (The first appearance of a lightsaber in the film is one of the most magical moments in cinematic history.)<br /> The generosity of "Star Wars" is the very reason why it has remained one of the biggest movies in history. Now what do I mean when I say generosity? Unlike most big blockbusters today, "Star Wars" respects its audiences. It doesn't just throw its plot at you and expect you to follow wooden characters. Instead, George Lucas teaches us about his imagination step by step, as we follow lovable characters that we begin to feel as real people.<br /> But since the opening of "Star Wars" in 1977, many people have tried to capture what Lucas achieved through the use of innovative special effects and a heart-warming narrative. Only certain movies like "E.T.", "Raiders of the Lost Ark", and "The Lord of the Rings" trilogy have captured at least a tenth of what "Star Wars" reached.<br /> Could "Star Wars" (and "Jaws" to a certain extent) though, have caused the death of cinema? Though filmmakers like Robert Altman, Francis Ford Coppola and Martin Scorsese still tried to achieve the great American movie, most directors have been shooting for the next "Star Wars". James Cameron is a perfect example of this, though none of his films have the amount of depth to them as "Star Wars" does.<br /> Lucas was credited at the time for writing corny dialogue (Harrison Ford actually blamed him for this) and yet he was nominated for an Oscar for Best Original Screenplay for "Star Wars". Though it didn't win, his screenplay has remained incredibly influential throughout the years. Almost every line in the movie is a near-classic one-liner, from "What a piece of junk!" to "That's no moon. It's a space station."<br /> The use of the music has also been quite influential (I could talk for hours just about the music in "Star Wars"). John Williams' original score harkened back to some classic grand scores such as Max Steiner's for "Gone With the Wind" and Maurice Jarre's for "Lawrence of Arabia." Whenever I hear a piece of music from the movie, I can quickly identify what section of the film is happening. The music has not only been influential in the sense of music composition. Many sections of the score have become staples in pop culture, as most people will recognize the Force theme, Princess Leia's theme, and of course, the main title theme.<br /> The amount of warmth that "Star Wars" gives to its audience is just overwhelming. From John Williams' iconic score (which several composers have been mimicking for years) to the shots on the planet Tatooine, every moment of the film gives an unimaginable amount of heart to whoever it is entertaining.<br /> I first saw the movie when I was 15 years old. Quickly, it became my favorite film of all time, and it still remains my favorite film. To watch "Star Wars" is to experience imagination at its greatest potential. The amount of movies that it has influenced over the years is too great to describe, and the amount of people it inspired is, at the very least, big. That is to say, "Star Wars" is not just a movie or a collection of movies. It is a way that people can see the world through. It is a new way to look at movies, to criticize them and to praise them. There have been many imitators over the years, but none have come close to the majesty that is "Star Wars."
