 | product/productId: 0780618548 | review/userId: A34GZPHWYPSY2T | review/summary: Hold my fuzzy pink sweater while I get my Glock | review/text: THE LONG KISS GOODNIGHT (1996) is one of those rare and extremely quirky, tongue-in-cheek black comedies that thrills, chills and splits your sides simultaneously. This is among the first of its kind, a silly spy contrivance with lots of action, witty dialogue that would have made Shakespeare envious, and absolutely no real logic to it.<br /><br />In short, Samantha Caine (a red-hot Geena Davis), a frumpy housewife, mother and gradeschool teacher, is really Charlotte "Charly" Baltimore - CIA assassin and Cold War ultra-weapon. An assassination attempt leaves her with amnesia and from what I can tell, she's been in her comfortable life for around five or six years.<br /><br />A failed series of private investigators has caused her to give her old identity "the long kiss goodnight" - until crusty old Mitch Henessy, P.I. (a hilarious and powerful Samuel L. Jackson) discovers what she wants to know. While he has some answers, even he will suffer from finding out who she is exactly.<br /><br />This film is a great ride, roller coaster all the way, of spy action, evil agencies and double-crossers, an angry president whose budget is tied up ("Can you say 'EDUCATION'?!" he sneers). As I say, look not for logic, there be none here - just pure fun like only the 1990s could really produce. The special effects are well worth it alone ... this is one of the first movies to utilize CGI in-action. (The other major film to do that was the original JURASSIC PARK.)<br /><br />While this film did borrow a tiny bit - more of a homage really - that it got from PULP FICTION (1994), it is highly original and excellent for all that.<br /><br />There is so much to love about this film, which makes you laugh out loud and makes your skin crawl at the same time. I was extremely taken with the appearance of Patrick Malahide (as CIA director Leland Perkins) because I actually had not seen him since he played Alfred Jingle in the 1984 tv film "The Pickwick Papers" (vid. my review). He's done a great deal of work, in fact, and here I thought he might be dead.<br /><br />Consider the top films of the year, which this thing had to vie with: THE ENGLISH PATIENT, FARGO, INDEPENDENCE DAY, MISSION: IMPOSSIBLE, the foolish TRAINSPOTTING and TWISTER. THE LONG KISS GOODNIGHT did not actually get buried, but because it was such a trend-setter, and so many films resulted with similar names, I think it got lost in the tidal wave.<br /><br />Don't let it be lost. Get it and savor it: you won't see its like, ever again.
