 | product/productId: 0790733897 | review/userId: AB4WQ9HGVCCD | review/summary: "Existential Cool on 2 Discs!" | review/text: In an interview with writer-director Lawrence Kasdan contained on the documentary included in this new package, Kasdan says "there's not an actor that's ever dreamed of being a movie star that hasn't studied Steve Mc Queen's performance in 'Bullitt' over and over again.....he makes the most mundane acts like getting out of a car seem cool...."<br /><br />Any male, say between the ages of 18 and 40, who first saw 'Bullitt' in 1968 was somehow effected by McQueen's performance and the overall laconic hipness of the film.<br /><br />I remember zipping out of the movie theater parking lot at breakneck speed and rushing to the nearest men's store to buy a trenchcoat.<br /><br />It was also reported that after the film opened, a number of actual plainclothes cops began showing up for work in turtlenecks.<br /><br />'Bullitt' is the quintissential movie star vehicle--the plot is muddled, the pacing at times is slow, the supporting performances, while good, are never quite fleshed out--but damn if McQueen's existential hip wattage doesn't shoulder the entire project singlehandedly--the man could do more with a glance than many actors with a half page of dialouge.<br /><br />This new 2 disc edition includes: a newly remastered print that is far brighter and crisper than the initial DVD release; an interesting commentary by director Peter Yates; a wonderul full length documentary "The Essence of Cool" featuring Robert Culp, Eli Wallach, Robert Vaughn, Mc Queen's first wife who helped guide his career, actor and close friend Don Gordon as well as many great film clips and still photos.<br /><br />Also included is a mini featurette "Steve Mc Queen's Committment To Reality" (also included in the originial DVD release) and a feature on film editing which has nothing to do with Mc Queen or "Bullitt" but who's to complain.<br /><br />Steve Mc Queen like Hendrix, Joplin, Morrison, Marilyn et all is one of those pop culture icons that became larger than life through their untimely passings--but in the case of Steve Mc Queen as "Bullitt" the phrase 'larger than life' is no cliche.
