 | product/productId: 6300183971 | review/userId: A1Z1NQJUJQ5CRO | review/summary: An epic that just doesn't cut it | review/text: Dune(released Dec/84),is an overly long and erratic tome that in the end fails to satisfy.It is chock full of stars like Jose Ferrer,Patrick Stewart,Linda Hunt,Kyle Maclachlin,Sting,Max Von Sydow,Dean Stockwell,Sean Young and many,many more,but the sheer immensity of the talent on hand still isn't enough to give this film more than just an average score.The book was first published in 1965 and I recall it was a must read among my buddies.The author wrote five more sequels,none of which this movie attempted to integrate...thank goodness!<br />The plot is a hard one to follow but in general terms it consists of one planet whose surface is mined for the spice melange,called Arrakis.It is highly valuable stuff and when production of it starts to waver,or at least the potential of a slow down is seen,the Emperor Shaddam is under scrutiny by its trading partners.A direct threat to his power is the Duke Atreides,who has a son who has foretold prophecies of the future that have affected the Emperor.The Emperor schemes to let the Duke take control of the mining operations on Arrakis.However Baron Harkonnen the sadistic ruler of another planet has been given permission by the Emperor to invade Arrakis and kill the Duke and his son and take control of the mining operations there.<br />The Duke,his son and mother arrive on Arrakis and are given a tour of the spice mining operations.The biggest threat to the miners are the gigantic worms that are attracted to sounds and have been known to destroy the machines and kill miners in the process.The Fremen are the inhabitants of Arrakis and up until now their numbers have been vastly underestimated.The Duke wants to make an alliance with the Fremen but before he can do that the Harkonnens attack.During this time the Duke is killed but his son and his mother escape into the deep deserts.While seeking refuge from a sandworm they meet up with a local tribe of Fremen.They take the dukes son to be a fulfillment of a long held prophecy,which coincides with the myriad of dreams the Dukes son has had all of his life.He is now the Muaddib and becomes leader of the Fremen.He leads a revolt against the Harkonnens and the Emperor and regains control of Arrakis for the Fremen.The film ends as rain,which hasn't fallen in centuries,comes down on an astonished populace.<br />Director David Lynch focuses I think too much on the characters of the film such as the Baron Harkonnen,played a little over the top by Ken McMillan,and leaves the plot to meander from one episode to the other.It seems to shift from an over the topper like the Baron to an understated and more subtle performance such as Dr Kynes,played nicely by Max Von Sydow,and back again.As a result the film is reduced to a roller coaster ride that can get boring awfully fast.<br />Technically the film is in its w/s a/r of 2:35:1 and needs a remastering as the film can be a bit too grainy at times.There are no extras to speak of.<br />In conclusion Dune is just an average film chock full of great talent that really had no where to go.Dune,to do the book(s)up right,should be given to a Peter Jackson,who did the Lord of the Rings up properly.He could do great things with this series of Sci-Fi classics,but if you're looking for Dune done properly,read the books;it hasn't been put onto celluloid yet!
